The problem seems to be benign at present because in all of the places where the function is used there are incoming Tensor ORT_ENFORCE where it checks that the number of dimensions is greater than zero. I will fix this though.
@atp798 Do you have a specific example where this causes a crash?
The problem seems to be widespread due to https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/2217
input_shape.Size() can return -1 as well to represent symbolic shapes. Check tensor_shape.cc.
Size() returns 1 if there are no dims. It only returns 0 if one or more dims have a value of 0.

> The problem seems to be benign at present because in all of the places where the function is used there are incoming Tensor ORT_ENFORCE where it checks that the number of dimensions is greater than zero. I will fix this though.
> @atp798 Do you have a specific example where this causes a crash?

Sorry, I haven't got one yet. I just read the code and found this.

> input_shape.Size() can return -1 as well to represent symbolic shapes. Check tensor_shape.cc.

Although in this case it's calculating an output size, so the shape would be concrete with no symbolic dimensions.

@atp798 do you still think there's an issue?

If there are no dims in the shape it represents a scalar, so Size() returns 1.
If there are dims, at this point in execution there will be no symbolic dimensions so the value returned by Size() will not be negative, and generally will be > 0. 
The edge case this check is handling is when a dimension has a value of 0, leading to Size() returning zero. This can happen for example if the first dimension represents the number of matches from a NonZero node. If that happens we know there are dimensions though, so accessing input_shape[0] is safe.
